Task: Create a set of Travel to Work Areas using Coombes and Bond algorithm

Travel to Work Areas are a group of localities which have been assigned to a region based on the maximisation of the interactions between them.

We are analysing the TTWA of Dublin to see the population’s relationship with where they live and where they work. We will use an algorithm to break Dublin into regions based on where people live and work. Each region’s size will indicate how many people both live and work in that region. We will set self containment and population parametres to determine how many regions will be created. There will be a trade off between size and self containment.

Brief explanation of the underlying algorithm:

The algorithm joins neighboring areas which satisfy the conditions set, based on community flows. The method uses two properties, self containment and number of people employed. Self containment is the proportion of workers who live and work in an area. We must set minimum and target values as parametres, for both properties, to run the algorithm.

The algorithm checks each area to see if it is over the minimum self containment parametre. If it is not it is assessed against the other neighbouring areas and is joined to the area which has the most important community flows. They are now considered one entity and the joined community flows are recalculated and the algorithm progresses.

In the first plot we can see TTWAs based on a target working population of 80,000 and 50% self containment.

We can see the Swords-Forrest area is the largest, indicating the least densely populated areas with working people travelling to work in that area. There are rural communities to the north of this area with low populations which would have been joined with communities with stronger work flows closer to the city centre. There may also be less large employment providers in the northern communities in this area.

The Blanchardstown - Blakestown area is the smallest area, followed closely by Lucan-Esker. The communities in these areas have a high population of workers with short travel to work distances. One cause of this could be the high volumes of housing estates and retail/ business parks in close proximity to each other.

In Dun Laoghaire-Sallynoggin West and Saggart the workers are travelling northwards. Dun Laoghaire specifically is influenced by the city centre.

The interesting one is the Balbriggan Rural area, there is a high population of workers who work in the area. I was surprised that this was a smaller area than Swords-Forrest. It would probably be worth exploring the population versus employed population in these areas to see why they performed differently under the algorithm.

There are some areas slightly fragmented which shows non-contiguity. These may need to be fine tuned. A multiple enclave of Dun Laoghaire-Sallynoggin West communities can be seen in the Swords-Forrest area.

There is also one enclave belonging to Blanchardstown- Blakestown and another belonging to Lucan-Esker in Dun Laoghaire - Sallynoggin.

Provide brief discussion of result:

Throughout all the examples, the Blanchardstown-Blakestown area has barely changed. It has stayed pretty consistent through all the parametre changes. This indicates, to me, a large population of employed people, who work in the area, evenly distributed through all the communities in the area.

The city centre has an influential pull on the areas to the south of the county, meaning many people living in the south county work in the city centre. The west of the county is more self-contained.

The areas to the north of the county changed the most dramatically when the parametres changed. There is a lot of rural communities and depending on target sizes these were pulled in different directions. The bigger the target population the bigger the areas in the north got.

The bigger the target population the less clusters created. Self containment has a lesser influence.
